If there's a tag containing quotes, let's say it's {{v"0.4.1-test.0"}} then Sourcetree reports:
{code:java}
git -c diff.mnemonicprefix=false -c core.quotepath=false -c credential.helper=sourcetree tag -d v"0.4.1-test.0"
One or more of this task's arguments is invalid. They cannot start with '-', and must follow git ref-format rules: https://www.kernel.org/pub/software/scm/git/docs/git-check-ref-format.html
Completed with errors, see above
{code}
One can't create such tag using SourceTree but the only way to remove it is git cli:
{code:java}
git tag -d v\"0.4.1-test.0\" && git push -v origin :refs/tags/v\"0.4.1-test.0\"
{code}
while it would be super easy to escape quotes on SourceTree side.

 Repro:
 # Check out any branch, say {{example_branch}}
 # In the dropdown to select which branch to show (i.e. "All Branches", etc.), select {{example_branch}}
 # Delete {{example_branch}} from within Sourcetree
 # A modal pops up saying something like "git fatal: bad revision {{example branch"}} or something similar.

Hi,
would be please possible to extend possibilities of Sourcetree called from command-line with manipulation of bookmarked repositories? I mean to add already existing repository to bookmarks or remove bookmark?
I.e.:
{{sourcetree --add-bookmark --type=<folder|Git|Mercurial> --name=<name> [--parent=<parent>] [--path=<path>] [--quit]}}
{{sourcetree --remove-bookmark --name=<name> [--quit]}}
Thanks.

When popping a stash I receive an error using the GUI. However, if I run the problematic command from the error in a terminal, it works fine. 

 

The error shown by the GUI is 
{noformat}
git -c diff.mnemonicprefix=false -c core.quotepath=false -c credential.helper=sourcetree stash pop stash@{0} 
One or more of this task's arguments is invalid. They cannot start with '-', and must follow git ref-format rules: https://www.kernel.org/pub/software/scm/git/docs/git-check-ref-format.html
Completed with errors, see above
{noformat}
 

I'm not sure how to provide more detail on this, so get in touch if you need further input.

Rather than opening a new terminal and running {{cd <directory>}}, SourceTree should simply use:
{code}
NSWorkspace.shared.openFile(<directory>, withApplication: "Terminal")
{code}
in Swift, or:
{code}
[[NSWorkspace sharedWorkspace] openFile:<directory> withApplication:@"Terminal"];
{code}
in Objective-C. This makes the output cleaner and is more stable. This way could also support using 3rd party Terminal utilities.

/Applications/SourceTree.app/Contents/Resources/bin/stgpg.sh contains flags 
{code:java}
--batch --no-tty{code}
This can affect the absence of a passphrase request.
